Just three weeks after Lucian Books & Wine received a semifinalist nod for Outstanding Wine Program from the James Beard Foundation, owners Jordan Smelt and Katie Barringer announced they will open Sargent next spring along the Eastside Beltline. 

Named for American portrait artist John Singer Sargent, the couple‚Äôs second Atlanta restaurant will become the latest edition to the New City development in the Old Fourth Ward. The sprawling Beltline complex is also home to MailChimp, plant shop The Victorian, Burle‚Äôs Bar, and the Forth Hotel with its restaurants Il Premio, Elektra, Moonlight, and Bar Premio.

Situated at the corner of 10th and Monroe beyond the entrance to Park Tavern in Midtown, the space unites the innovative coffee pop-up highlighting Asian specialty coffee with the mobile Latin street food cart in one set location. As a mini collective of entrepreneurs, Stroll provides space to whoever wants to get involved, adding to the collaborative nature of the project. ‚û°Ô∏è Read the story from Rough Draft dining reporter Sarra Sedghi at the link in bio.

Did you shop Small Business Saturday?

Atlanta Beltline Marketplace partnered with Atlanta Indie Market to feature over 30 small businesses across three different locations on the Beltline this past Saturday.

Small business owners say local markets such as these are essential to their business, especially as the economy has made it more difficult to afford supplies and ingredients, and as such, turn a profit.

Atlanta Indie Market sets up on the Beltline every second Saturday of the month with local vendors, games, buskers and music.

Tell us your favorite local business in the comments!
Slices and more on the Beltline https://t.co/AGDc18TyWG

A day after Black Friday, the Atlanta BeltLine held its annual Small Business Saturday event.

The event features dozens of local entrepreneurs at three pop-up sites along the BeltLine.

One of the locations was under Freedom Ridge Bridge in northeast Atlanta.

Adam Size is the owner of Atlanta Burns, a locally produced hot sauce company.

#atlanta #atlantanews #atlantanewsfirst #smallbusiness

‚ÄúBig corporations get a big big focus on Black Friday, so Small Business Saturday is a push to remind our communities and neighborhoods about the small businesses, mom-and-pops, because they‚Äôre really the soul of our city in Atlanta‚Äù said Kara Lively, director of economic development for Atlanta Beltline, Inc.

The Atlanta Beltline‚Äôs vision for its largest piece of property is beginning to take shape.

The Beltline acquired 425 Chappell Rd. three years ago for nearly $26 million from developer Brock Built Homes. The Beltline envisions up to 1,100 residences on the site, with nearly a third reserved as affordable housing, alongside 5,000 square feet of commercial space.

The organization filed paperwork last week outlining a $270 million plan to develop the land. The Beltline estimates the entire development could be finished by 2030.

The year is 2013, Atlanta is crawling out from economic recession, and James Beard‚Äìnominated chef @chefhectorsantiago has recently closed Pura Vida, his beloved tapas staple in Poncey-Highland. The more Santiago ponders his next move, the more a concept called @poncecitymarket sounds appealing‚Äîlargely because it would be connected to @atlantabeltline‚Äôs brand-new Eastside Trail. ‚ÄúThe Beltline brought that kind of cosmopolitan, walking-around feel of a city,‚Äù recalls Santiago. ‚ÄúIt really changed the city to me. And I wanted to be in the center of it.‚Äù As for Santiago, his Ponce City bet paid off. @elsuperpan_pcm, his Latin bar for sandwiches and cocktails, has become a cornerstone (literally, on a can‚Äôt-miss corner) of the food hall, and joins original tenants such as @bellinaalimentari, @mineroatl, Jia, and W.H. Stiles Fish Camp, which are still feeding roughly 10,000 daily visitors. Santiago has claimed another corner space for a second concept, tapas bar @lametroatl and he estimates his original fast-casual business tallies 300 orders per day on average. ‚ÄúWe have the traffic of being at the airport,‚Äù Santiago says. ‚ÄúAnd every year it grows‚Äîwell, apart from the pandemic.‚Äù‚Å†

post_body_text: Happy birthday, #PonceCityMarket and #KrogStreetMarket! Here's a look back on the last decade.

Atlanta, the de facto capital of the American South, is secure in its position as a nexus of civil rights history, capitalist hustle, Black creativity, and (thanks to generous state tax credits) TV and film production. 

Beyond the traffic-choked highways, Atlanta‚Äôs older, more central neighborhoods offer abundant charm, thrumming with dining, nightlife and art. A key catalyst has been the Atlanta Beltline, the partly constructed 22-mile walking and biking path that has connected old parts of town in fresh ways, spurring revitalization and giving locals and visitors alike a place to enjoy the city outside their cars.

Expect a cloudy weekend with temps in the upper 60s to lower 70s, with a chance of rain on Sunday....

The Atlanta Beltline has purchased a shuttered Buckhead nightclub where it plans to build a key segment of the Northwest Trail.

On Thursday, Mayor Andre Dickens and Atlanta Beltline Inc. President and CEO Clyde Higgs announced the acquisition of the Elleven45 Lounge at 2110 Peachtree Road NW. The Beltline acquired the roughly one-acre site for $11 million.

The controversial nightclub was the scene of a fatal shooting in the early morning hours of May 12. Two people were killed and two wounded. One arrest was made in the shooting. The city of Atlanta shut the nightclub down months later after a Fulton Superior Court judge ruled the venue a public nuisance. 

The nightclub property was needed to complete Segment 2 of the Northwest Trail located near Piedmont Atlanta Hospital, the largest employer in the Beltline Planning Area.

This segment is a 0.7-mile stretch being built outside the railroad corridor starting at the southwest corner of Bobby Jones Golf Course, running east along Colonial Homes Circle, and then passing under Peachtree Road. A construction date for Segment 2 is not yet known.

#Atlanta has purchased the site of the former #Elleven45 Lounge as part of the #Atlanta #BeltLine‚Äôs expansion into #Buckhead, specifically focusing on affordable housing and commercial development. The #BeltLine has acquired nearly 90 acres of land, including 20 acres in 2023, to ensure long-term affordability and equitable development. 

One notable project is the affordable mixed-use development at 425 Garson Drive in Buckhead/Lindbergh, which will feature permanently affordable housing and commercial space near the Lindbergh MARTA station and along the future Northeast Trail. 

The BeltLine has also exceeded its 2023 affordable housing goal, creating 407 affordable homes within the BeltLine Tax Allocation District (TAD) and bringing the total number of affordable units to 3,555.

@theatlantaopera will transform the historic Bobby Jones Clubhouse into a performing arts center with a recital hall, theatre venue, education spaces, and administrative and rehearsal areas for the Opera.

Located in Peachtree Battle on Woodward Way along the Atlanta Beltline, the facility is expected to cost $45 million with core funding already secured, according to a press release from the Opera. Announcements of the donors and a capital campaign will be announced soon, and the project is estimated to be completed by the summer of 2027.

The long-vacant clubhouse, which served the Bobby Jones Golf Course in Atlanta Memorial Park, was built in the Grecian revival built in the early 1900s.

The 17,000 square foot clubhouse will transform into a 56,000+ square foot complex housing a 200-seat recital hall, administrative offices, a costume shop, a Ô¨Ålm studio, a rehearsal hall, and garden spaces. Theater Projects and A‚Äôkustiks, LLC., are developing the recital hall as a premiere venue to present classical singers and musicians, jazz ensembles, lectures and spoken word artists, and other performing arts.

How the Promenade Plante√© and Viaduc des Arts in Paris inspired the Atlanta Beltline. ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ #Atlanta #Georgia #ATL #History #Anecdote #Anecdotes #VisitAtlanta #AtlantaGuide #GeorgiaOnMyMind #story #Stories #Tales #interesting #education #documentary #civilwar #locomotive #trains #train #Beltline #AtlantaBeltline
GoogleAudioText: It's hard to imagine Atlanta without the belt line, but if it wasn't for one Georgia Tech students trips to the city of lights, it's possible it will have never have come to be. With the spread of the interstate highway system in the 1960s and 70s, many of the railway lines on which Atlanta was built soon became abandoned. From 1994, a young Georgia Tech student by the name of Ryan Gravel was studying abroad in Paris, living just a block from an abandoned railway viaduct near the banks of the river Sen. Five years later, now as a Georgia Tech graduate student studying architecture and city planning, Gravel returned to Paris and saw how the former railway relic had been transformed into a half mile elevated walking garden, with arts related businesses and studios below. Gravel saw how the project revitalized the surrounding neighbourhoods and wrote his master's thesis on how the same could be done with Atlanta's abandoned belt line, which was built in the decades following the Civil War to alleviate rail congestion downtown. His ideas became the blueprint for the belt line we know today.

The Atlanta City Council has approved new ordinances that could significantly reshape the city's core by restricting where data centers can be developed. The legislation, which bars new data centers from being built near the BeltLine and within a half-mile of MARTA stations, is designed to prioritize human spaces over industrial use.

Atlanta's data center market has been one of the fastest-growing in the nation, driven by increased demand for digital infrastructure. However, city leaders are concerned that these developments could encroach on valuable urban space that is better used for public amenities.

The new restrictions will take effect once Atlanta Mayor Andre Dickens signs them.

Earlier this week, @westsidefuturefund and Atlanta's historic Westside hit an exciting milestone as we broke ground on a new high-quality 24-unit affordable housing development at 646 Echo Street in English Avenue.

This project embodies WFF's vision: restoring the historic Westside to a community Dr. King would be proud to call home. With deeply affordable units - 20% at 30% AMI, 30% at 60% AMI, 50% at 80% AMI - near the Westside Beltline Connector Trail, we're creating opportunities for inclusive growth.

Thank you to Mayor @andreforatlanta and Councilman @byronamos for joining us and delivering thoughtful remarks, and for your continued leadership and steadfast support.

post_body_text: Guest Column:  The vital role of light rail in Atlanta‚Äôs BeltLine neighborhoods  @BeltLIneRailNow  https://t.co/luyhs63IUn
Bird walk on the Atlanta BeltLine with our Birds and Brews event! Learning about Chimney Swifts and the many birds that spend their summers in and around Atlanta.

I believe the BeltLine is a public good, one which has already transformed our city for the better. Building the BeltLine has, at its core, built new communities and connections in our city, bringing us closer together in a way that I think even the most optimistic projections couldn‚Äôt have anticipated.

While division across the country has made big wins more rare, I believe the Atlanta BeltLine shines as a beacon of what is possible when we let our imaginations loose. The first step to rebuilding our divided communities is connecting them, a promise that the BeltLine is on track to fulfill. 

#AtlantaBeltLine #CommunityConnection #UrbanTransformation #PublicGood #AtlantaUnited

Is Atlanta‚Äôs town square the BeltLine? Is it Piedmont Park? Is it someplace else? @PerkinsWill ponders this question in the latest installment of its series on the role of civic space and parks in Atlanta  #sponsored  https://t.co/dsTgNMq0XF

RT @AtlantaBeltline: New look. New website.

Same important mission.

Explore the new Atlanta Beltline brand at https://t.co/1uPxS9Cuiv.‚Ä¶

William Coleman was denied bond in court Monday. Coleman is accused of stabbing and killing an unhoused man Friday near the BeltLine, according to a spokesperson for the BeltLine. There is security footage of the alleged crime. 

A representative from the Georgia Department of Corrections told 11Alive that Coleman left the Atlanta Transitional Center, on Ponce de Leon Avenue, on June 22. and never returned. The center is not gated and sits near several business and housing units. 

In a statement Monday, GDOC said transitional centers assist offenders in returning to society in a structured setting.

"Unfortunately, some individuals make a decision not to return to the facility from their jobs or otherwise leave the facility," the statement reads. "When that occurs, the GDC dedicates all of our Fugitive Unit resources toward immediate action and recapture, to include communication with our law enforcement partners in the community."

Intown Atlanta GNPS Native Garden Tour
Saturday, June 8, 2024, 9:30am to 3:30pm

The Intown Atlanta Chapter of the Georgia Native Plant Society  will be hosting a self-guided garden tour of five beautiful habitats created to support biodiversity, pollinators and other wildlife. Four habitats are private urban gardens and certified GNPS Native Plant Habitats. The fifth is the new Trees Atlanta headquarters, thoughtfully landscaped with native perennials, shrubs, and trees. 

The gardens are located near Atlanta‚Äôs Southside and Westside Beltline Trail, with restaurants, shops, and breweries you may want to visit as part of your adventure. At each property, the homeowner or primary gardener and GNPS volunteers will be available to answer questions and point out highlights. Learn more or purchase tickets at the GNPS Garden Tour link in our profile.

Invest Atlanta approves official developers for a mixed-use project that will transform Murphy Crossing, a 20-acre site adjacent to the @AtlantaBeltLine Westside Trail and near the Oakland City and West End MARTA stations.   @InvestAtlanta  @delaneytarr   https://t.co/Iwr4VSvfpa

Mayor Andre Dickens announced Monday plans to build four new MARTA stations during his annual State of the City address. 
https://t.co/JFAFlTAmO6
This is what reconnecting communities looks like! MARTA is a key to transportation equity and economic opportunity for tens of thousands of riders.

New tiny door alert! üåûüåô Our collab with @occasionalsuperstar was featured this week in @artsatlanta as a "hard to find mural that's worth the effort" üòÑ We spent long afternoons brainstorming what to do with this cool old silo. The mural and tiny doors (yes, they open!!) are representative of day and night, of moving forward in a city with rich history, shining a light on what's to come. Fabian's mural work inside the silo tells a visual story of Atlanta moving forward. We're only showing the tiny door here, the rest is a surprise to discover when you arrive! You can find it at 680 Hamilton, facing the Beltline.  @thepenmanatl

post_body_text: NEWS: Sen. Ossoff, Senator Reverend Raphael Warnock, and Congresswoman Nikema Williams today announced new Federal grants to upgrade transportation & recreation infrastructure for Georgia families ‚Äî including historic grants to fund phase 1 of The Stitch & a new multi-use trail connecting the AtlantaBeltLine with the Flint River Trail. A $157 million Federal investment will fund Phase 1 of The Stitch project, which aims to reconnect downtown Atlanta by capping the I-75/I-85 interstate with a new 4-acre park and multimodal improvements across the street network with better connectivity to MARTA‚Äôs Civic Center. A $50 million Federal investment in the Southside Trail will help advance the Atlanta Regional Commission's project to build a new multi-use trail ‚Äî which would help connect schools, hospitals, job centers, and MARTA rail between the BeltLine and the Flint River Trail. Sens. Ossoff and Rev. Warnock also announced additional grants for continued planning of projects to upgrade infrastructure across Georgia. The City of Savannah will receive a $1.8 million Federal investment for Savannah's I-16 flyover project, which aims to remove the flyover exit ramp over Martin Luther King, Jr. Boulevard to Montgomery Street & the associated adjacent ramps to improve connectivity. Athens-Clarke County will receive an $800,000 Federal grant to continue planning infrastructure upgrades along Hawthorne and Oglethorpe Avenues in downtown Athens, improving connectivity and increasing community safety. Macon-Bibb County will receive a $500,000 Federal grant for continued planning of upgrades to the Pleasant Hill Neighborhood, with plans to reconnect the community with Macon-Bibb County‚Äôs downtown business district.

GoogleAudioText: Well faith this afternoon, residents along the Silver Comet Belt Line Expansion Trail are voicing concerns over this new project with construction already underway. Neighbors say they hope there will be enough safety measures to keep drivers, cyclists and pedestrians safe. Now, we spoke with one woman who says this is personal. My father was actually hit by a semi crossing a road when he was on the Silver Comet Trail and they even had a little crosswalk sign up. He was listening to headphones and just walking and it didn't occur to him. So 11 alive did reach out to the Path Foundation to ask about safety measures that they plan to implement in the building out the connector trail, but we haven't heard back. We of course, will let you know when we do.

GoogleAudioText: The good news though, the weather, there's no snow or ice storm but that frigid air sufficient cause for us to send our man Doug Richards into the city for coverage of how we're all handling this unusual chill. Doug joining us now from northeast Atlanta. How are you making it out there? Doug, I feel compelled to report that the breeze that Ashley was talking about is blowing directly in my face right now. And if you see a little glistening underneath, uh, my eyeball, uh, it is uh, tears of joy because I love my job so much. Uh, we have talked a lot on this station about, uh how unpleasant the weather has been. Uh, the, the colder temperatures, how dangerous it can be. Um And tonight we found that in spite of all that people were still at least a few people out and about because hey, it is Saturday night in Atlanta. It's cold. I need a different word. Very nippy. Yeah. Frigid, uh, painful. This was the Atlanta Beltline downright empty compared to almost any other Saturday evening trying to get our exercise despite the weather. Yeah. Yeah. Was it tempted to just say No, not tonight. It was very tempting, but usually the beltline is just, you know, so packed on a Saturday. I saw that the sun was setting and then we was really just coming to shoot a couple of pictures. We spotted two different photographers capturing images of women modeling, not exactly Arctic style clothing. I feel good. I'm just acting like it's not cold. Is it more important to be warm or to look great? Um I like to be comfortable, but I like to look good. I'm gonna go in a warm anyway. So it's only gonna get colder right now. How would you describe the weather without using the word cold, bone chilling? I would agree with nippy freezing. It's, it's like froze. Definitely glad we came out, but I'm definitely also excited to get back in as well. I hope tonight's weather coverage uh has moved you to tears as it has me. Uh I'm gonna follow the advice of that. Last guy talked about how nice it was to get to be outside and how nice it will be to uh go in, see you all later live in northeast Atlanta. Back to you. Doug, Richards gracing us with your presence on a Saturday night, freezing his anatomy off. All right. Doug, thank you.

The Fulton County District 4 Office, in partnership with The Atlanta BeltLine Partnership held our final senior BeltLine tour of the year. I always look forward to engaging with our seniors through this highly interactive and scenic tour of the BeltLine. 

This 3-hour tour gives Fulton County Seniors the opportunity to see the growth and expansion of the Atlanta BeltLine, connect with neighborhoods throughout the city, and engage with each other through shared stories and experiences.

I am grateful for the continued growth and participation in this very popular event, and I look forward to getting even more seniors on the BeltLine next year!

Benchmarking at its best! Last week I joined members of the St. Petersburg Downtown Partnership in Atlanta for a tour of Truist Park and the Battery, followed by a visit to the Beltline and Ponce City Market. After the group left, I stayed on for the National League of Cities‚Äô annual City Summit for workshops on homelessness and placemaking, an aviation roundtable with the FAA and more. So many interesting observations and ideas from this trip!

The past few days I‚Äôve been learning with fellow city councilmembers from across the nation at the National League of Cities City Summit in Atlanta! Topics included touring the Atlanta BeltLine (a fantastic case study for merging connectivity, recreation, natural resources, and economic development), visiting two city parks with stormwater and drinking water co-purposes, meeting our community housing needs, sustainability and climate action, accessing unprecedented levels of federal funding, and more. I‚Äôm looking forward to bringing good ideas home to our community! Pictured: Melissa Cheatham, Overland Park City Council, Ward 2 Councilman Eric Bunch-4th In District Kansas City Councilman Johnathan Duncan Stacey Abrams

GoogleAudioText: Well, it is time to fall back. Daylight saving time officially ends on Sunday at 2 a.m. But the changing time can create confusion among those who have dementia or Alzheimer's disease. It's called sundowning. And symptoms can include difficulty sleeping, anxiety, agitation, hallucinations, pacing and disorientation. You have less sensory input when the sun goes down. This is what the sun downing term refers to when the sun goes down, things get darker, they're more shadows. You can't interpret a process as well as you used to. But there are ways caregivers in families can help first keep a predictable routine. You wanna go to bed, get up and eat around the same times each day, next plan activities during the morning and early afternoon. So your loved one will be sleepy at night limit daytime, napping, caffeine and sugar and turn on a night light to help lower agitation. That may happen when it's dark and make sure that hearing aids and glasses, anything like that are close by to avoid additional sensory deprivation.

Atlanta BeltLine, Inc. is calling for businesses interested in participating in its BeltLine MarketPlace program.
 
BeltLine MarketPlace is a unique opportunity for local entrepreneurs to get affordable retail space on the Atlanta BeltLine, with access to the more than 2 million people who visit the trail each year. Selected businesses also participate in a business incubator program that teaches them everything from marketing to cash flow.
 
Applications for the program will be accepted from October 16 to October 30, 2023, online at www.beltline.org/marketplace. The application process will be administrated in partnership with The Village Market, the small business incubation partner from the inaugural season.
 
To qualify for the BeltLine MarketPlace, businesses must meet the following criteria:
Be in operation for at least one year
Have an annual revenue of at least $50,000
Employ a minimum of two individuals capable of working a minimum of five hours per day, seven days a week at a MarketPlace location
 
The BeltLine encourages all businesses to apply, especially those considered to be historically socially and economically disadvantaged, such as Minority Business Enterprises, women, veterans, and LGBTQ+ community members.

post_body_text: Unlike the previous administration, which only talked about infrastructure, the Biden Administration is taking action. The U.S. Department of Transportation will send more than $2.2 billion in grants to state, tribal and local governments under a grant program that was expanded under the 2021 bipartisan infrastructure law which our Congressman, Drew Ferguson, opposed. Georgia projects in line for funding include an Atlanta trail project, an Oconee Heights pedestrian path and development of a multimodal transportation plan for Thomasville. The Atlanta trail project was among those receiving $25 million. The project, which has a total cost of $70.7 million, will add 4.8 miles to the BeltLine Northeast Trail, which is accessible to pedestrians and bicycles. The project will create new access to transit and to jobs, schools and other services in an area with 5,000 affordable housing units nearby.

üí¢ ‚ÄúA BLM mural along a popular section of the Atlanta Beltline has faded in part because the slogan was done as a community project and does not have a maintenance plan by the city, a BeltLine spokesperson tells Axios Atlanta.

Austin removed its Black Austin Matters and Black Artists Matter installations, which were first put in place in June 2020, as part of scheduled road resurfacing, a city spokesperson tells Axios Austin‚Äôs Asher Price.

Seattle had its mural repainted last year, and city officials redirected traffic onto the parking lanes around it.

Cars can now similarly drive on Washington D.C.'s Black Lives Matter Plaza ‚Äî a stretch of 16th Street NW near the White House ‚Äî but the once-painted mural became a permanent concrete installation in 2021.

The bottom line: The Black Lives Matter murals were helpful symbols, but they‚Äôre ultimately only as useful as the tangible changes they bring about, Rashad Robinson, president of Color of Change, an advocacy organization, tells Axios.

post_body_text: A long-awaited plan to link the Atlanta BeltLine and Silver Comet Trail is gaining ground.  https://t.co/61iqBLDJx4
Here's how the Cobb County trail would connect to the Atlanta trail.
GoogleAudioText:
The presidential election
isn't until 2024, but the prep work starts now. Today, Georgia's Secretary of Se outlined a bunch of things the state is already doing to make e the upcoming election is secure. The state is going
to perform
what it calls election system health chs for all of Georgia's 159 counti. State elections officials
will examine the election management systems, ballot marking devices and scan. They're also going to go througd make sure the states voting mace software hasn't been
changed or updated. The state is also going
to be testing out updated voting machine soft, but officials say that process d take 10s of thousands of hours, so the new software won't be used until after the election.

I was honored to join everyone in the celebration of the groundbreaking of Atlanta BeltLine Southside Trail.

I was recently appointed to the Atlanta Beltline Board of Directors and I am excited about the new construction of 1.1 mile section of unpaved trail. The Atlanta Beltline marks our commitment to support creating a thriving and progressive space for residents.

As we continue to progress with this project, I look forward to it‚Äôs completion and continued growth in inclusivity, equitability, and connectivity in the City of Atlanta and Fulton County. 

Thank you to Clyde Higgs, The Atlanta BeltLine team, City of Atlanta Mayor Dickens, and partners for continuing to build a more equitable and inclusive Atlanta and engaging partners by delivering transformative public infrastructure that enhances mobility, fosters culture, and improves connections to economic opportunity.

Some bad ideas never die. MARTA released details last fall on a plan to extend its streetcar 2.5 miles to Atlanta‚Äôs Beltline.

The first line of the Atlanta Streetcar system was implemented in 2015 and has been a terribly inefficient public transit program since its implementation. 

The numbers speak for themselves:

- The cost of the first 2.7 miles exceeded estimates at $99 million, or $36.7 million a mile, in 2015. In 2023, estimated costs ballooned to between $88 million to $107.5 million a mile for the proposed expansion with total project costs ranging from $176 million to $230 million.
- Even when it was free, ridership was significantly below capacity, and now that the line costs $1 a ride, ridership has sunk to an average of 400 riders a day in 2022. 
- The system has an average traveling speed of 5 mph. Considering the average human walking speed is 2.5 to 4 mph, it‚Äôs not unfair to say Atlanta‚Äôs streetcars are one of the slowest forms of public transportation available.

Rather than an expensive project that will serve a limited area and has limited demand by people living there, we should be looking at solutions that are a better fit for commuters of necessity, will actually reduce car usage within the city and be cost effective for taxpayers.

Read more: https://www.georgiapolicy.org/news/atlanta-streetcar-grand-plans-and-failed-ambitions/

I know how much my Seniors loved the BeltLine Tours and I really wanted to work towards bringing them back. We haven't had the chance to do any since the pandemic and I'm so happy we were able to make it happen this year! 

I partnered with Atlanta BeltLine Partnership to bring Seniors a 3-hour tour of the Atlanta BeltLine Westside Trail. The event gave Fulton County Seniors an opportunity to see everything the Westside Trail has to offer. This fun, interactive, guided tour also taught Seniors how they can engage in BeltLine activities. 

Thank you to Michael Davis Atlanta BeltLine Partnership & Pittsburgh Yards for assisting with our 1st tour since 2019!

Registration for the Senior Beltline Tour this weekend is full!

If you are interested in joining the next tour please visit The Senior BeltLine Tour Eventbrite Link and add your name to the waitlist.

To add yourself to the waitlist click this link https://SeniorBeltlineTour2022.eventbrite.com.
1. Select "Reserve a Spot" in the top right corner.
2. Select "1 reservation for 2023 General Admission" and click "Register" at the bottom.
3. Fill out the contact information and check to see if you've received an email response. *Note: Make sure to check your spam or other folder.
4. Lastly, make sure to check your email regularly to see if you've received a ticket for the next Senior BeltLine Tour!

Commissioner Natalie Hall Presents The Senior Atlanta BeltLine Tour

Fulton County District 4 Commissioner Natalie Hall partners with the Atlanta BeltLine Partnership to bring seniors a 3-hour tour of the Atlanta BeltLine Westside Trail. This event will begin Friday, December 16, 2022, at 10 am at Pittsburgh Yards, 352 University Ave SW, Atlanta, GA 30310.

Fulton County seniors will have an opportunity to see everything the Westside Trail has to offer. This fun, interactive, guided tour will also teach the seniors of Fulton County how they can engage in BeltLine activities. This event is first come first serve and is open to Fulton County
Seniors (aged 55 and older).

If interested, please register here! You must be atleast 55 years old to join https://SeniorBeltlineTour2022.eventbrite.com

post_body_text: Warnock Steered $16 Million to Project That Benefited Co-Owner of Church‚Äôs Controversial Apartment Complex‚ÄîToday, Team Herschel released the following statement highlighting an article from The Washington Free Beacon titled: "Warnock Steered $16 Million to Project That Benefited Co-Owner of Church‚Äôs Controversial Apartment Complex.‚Äù Georgia Democratic senator Raphael Warnock steered $16.4 million in federal earmarks to a project that benefited the co-owner of his controversial low-income apartment complex. "The funding was intended to construct a trail connecting a residential and commercial complex known as "Pittsburgh Yards" with other portions of Atlanta's BeltLine. The developer of Pittsburgh Yards is Columbia Ventures, part of the Columbia group of companies that co-owns and operates a low-income housing complex with Warnock's church. "The funding raises questions about whether Warnock's business relationship with Columbia had any bearing on his funding decision. Warnock did not respond to a request for comment. "Warnock's Ebenezer Baptist Church, where he serves as senior pastor and CEO, in 2005 'formed a partnership with Columbia Residential to rehabilitate [a] dilapidated high-rise' and turned the building into low-income apartments. Ebenezer and Columbia are co-owners of the business through a joint venture, with Ebenezer owning 99 percent and Columbia owning the remaining 1 percent, according to a state grant application filed by the entities in August. "Last November, Warnock and Sen. Jon Ossoff (D., Ga.) announced that they had helped secure the funding for the trail project, which would 'construct approximately two miles of the Southside Trail component of the Atlanta BeltLine from Pittsburgh Yards to Boulevard Crossing Park.'" "Raphael Warnock is a corrupt hypocrite who only cares about himself, not the people of Georgia," said campaign spokesman Will Kiley. "Warnock lines his pockets and the pockets of his allies while attempting to evict low-income tenants in the building he oversees. Since coming to office, Warnock has doubled his income while Georgia families struggle to make ends meet. Raphael Warnock needs to be held accountable by the 'media' and the people of Georgia for his lies."
MARTA and the city of Atlanta are working on an east expansion of the streetcar which would run parallel to the Beltline.

post_body_text: Opponents say it‚Äôs a mistake to invest more money in a little-used streetcar that has failed to live up to expectations since it began service eight years ago.
Long-sought plans for transit on the Atlanta Beltline are taking a big step forward as MARTA plans to extend the downtown streetcar to Ponce City Market.
Multinational beer and pub chain BrewDog opened its first Atlanta location on the Beltline Eastside Trail.

The west side of the Atlanta BeltLine officially opened on Tuesday. Read the full story at http://bit.ly/3hjjCAv

post_body_text: A new mural along the Atlanta BeltLine in Downtown Atlanta is paying tribute to the life of Migos rapper Takeoff as Atlanta‚Äôs mayor‚Äôs adds his voice to those concerned over the violence.  https://t.co/jPOjtBeRZX

A pair of local artists painted the mural this week in tribute to the Migos rapper who died in a Houston shooting.

The painting appears along the Westside BeltLine in the Old Fourth Ward neighborhood.

11Alive is Where Atlanta Speaks. We believe that news shouldn‚Äôt be a one-way conversation, but a dialogue with you. Join in, share your thoughts and connect with new perspectives.

GoogleAudioText: death has impacted people all around the world from fans to fellow rappers to people who are just tired of gun violence some are now using his death to find ways to honor the late rapper we spoke to one local artist who's using his talents to try to find some healing it was just something for Atlanta and it was part of the culture so I wanted to really you know capture his Essence and you know give some that the city can honor and come down and and truly appreciate it so I remember hearing Amigos first time in Middle School it was the first time I really fell in love for like with like the new sound of Atlanta really because the Amigos created a new song of Atlanta and without takeoff's death it's really just like an end of era really like I came in the middle of the night to put it up and just so people can't wake up and have a chance to come and put fires out the candles out that's a fan of the music you know it's always going to be tough you know I really like respected his craft and everything like that so yeah it's just it's really tough it's tough It's really tough on the city well it's not about me as far it's for takeoff at the end of the day it's for him you know it's for his family you know as much respect to them and prayers go out to everybody who's morning his loss right now so you know just something spoke to me you know I'm saying like I said being a fan listen to his his music and I just feel like I had to go out and do it and it's just something that you don't think about you just go do and that's what everybody should start doing just believing in ourselves and doing it

---Twenty-three years ago, Atlanta-native and architecture and urban planning student Ryan Gravel had an experience that opened his mind to what urban living could be.
"My senior year I spent abroad in Paris and lived without a car for a year and traveled by train everywhere," says Gravel. "And within a month of arriving, I had lost 15 pounds. I was in the best shape of my life because I was walking everywhere, and the role of the physical city was made clear to me in a way it really had never been before."
For his Georgia Tech master's thesis, Gravel sketched out a plan to make Atlanta more like Paris. He proposed redeveloping the land along the city's historic rail lines to create a 22-mile loop called the Atlanta BeltLine. He proposed turning the city's abandoned industrial areas and single-family home neighborhoods into business districts and walking trails. And he proposed connecting downtown to the rest of the city all with a new train running along the entire Atlanta BeltLine.
"I never imagined we would actually do it," says Gravel.
But they did‚Äîfor the most part. Cathy Woolard, who was president of the Atlanta City Council, read Gravel's thesis and decided to use it as a blueprint to remake much of the city. Today, the Atlanta BeltLine is a walking and biking trail, parts of which are bordered by retail and condos.
But one piece of Gravel's grand vision didn't get built: The train.
Today, Gravel runs a co-working and event space along the BeltLine, which also serves as a gathering place for urbanists interested in making Atlanta less dependent on cars. He says that the train line is essential for improving city life.
"In those early days, when we built the movement behind the [BeltLine] project, it was around transit," says Gravel.
The three COVID relief bills set aside $69 billion in federal funding for local transit agencies to operate and add to their transportation systems, meaning that Atlanta might finally get its train‚Äîwith many American taxpayers who will never step foot on it picking up much of the tab.
Many American cities have used federal money in the past to build rail transit lines that suffer from dismal ridership, that are expensive to maintain, and that are a major drain on their budgets.

half of track there's a good chance that Transit ridership will never fully come back post pandemic because so many fewer people are commuting to jobs even in New York City paid bus and Subway ridership is at 55 percent of its pre-pandemic levels Nationwide Transit ridership is at about 69 percent of what it was before covet rail Transit Nationwide has taken a particularly bad hit with ridership decreasing by almost 50 percent between 2011 and 2020 while non-rail Transit decreased by about 30 percent that Trend applies in Atlanta where Marta's bus ridership decreased by 39 percent post covid while rail decreased by about 62 percent before covid only five percent of Americans working days were spent at home researchers at Stanford analyzed poll data and concluded that now about half of Americans work at home at least once a week and about a quarter are fully remote the pandemic also accelerated the decade-long trend of Americans moving from cities to lower density suburbs including the area surrounding the city of Atlanta which saw population loss in its Urban core for the first time in a decade between 2020 and 2021 Rao says it's just a blip this Corridor which is half a mile wide will contain between 23 and 25 percent of the population of this whole city by mid-century and that kind of density will only work sustainably if we provide the Transit downtown Atlanta is booming you have more freedom if you can telework so people they go where they want to go I know that's surprising for a lot of people but people do want to be downtown they want to be on the Beltline they want to be here there's so much to do you can walk you can ride scooters you can ride your bike I walk the Beltline practically four times a week it's pretty integral in my life I like the skateboarding just have fun yeah and be drunk while Ponce City Market is a popular destination much of the loop is still a nature trail with nothing but single family homes around it gravel's Master thesis opens with a history of Atlanta Transportation pointing out that street cars were profitable in many American cities before they were displaced by roads and cars is that something that you think we can ever get back to where there could be an actual you know profitable street car um it's a good question um from my personal Viewpoint um I think it I think there's a shared good that comes with public investment in transit and so I'm fully supportive of public transit but like the military like highways like all kinds of things there are things that are good for all of us that we should be investing in collectively this wasn't always the case in the 19th century Urban transit systems were privately owned and operated companies would sometimes lose money at the fare box to encourage ridership but make it back by speculating in land that increased in value because of the new train station when local governments did build infrastructure they would sometimes pay for it by levying special assessments on land owners who benefited Rouse Coalition is proposing just such a special Levy along the Beltline but it would cover just 10 percent of the projected 2.5 billion dollar construction cost Federal taxpayers would foot 40 percent of the bill if the local stakeholders who stand to benefit from increased property values had to fit more of the bill maybe they would think twice while rail and city buses consistently lose money buses that move people between cities are still privately owned and operated at a profit Amtrak on the other hand loses close to a billion dollars annually and relies on federal subsidies the bill I'm about to sign along is proof that's despite the cynics Democrats and Republicans can come together and deliver results it makes the most significant investment in passenger rail in the past 50 years and in public transit ever feigenbaum says many politicians seem to care less about whether Transportation projects are best serving their constituents and much more about the spectacle if I'm a politician and I'm running for re-election I get to go to a ribbon cutting ceremony and say I did this and I get to send out a postcard to all of the voters in my district and say I did this I'm here working for you using your taxpayer money in dubious ways whereas if you're talking about operations there's no ribbon cuttings with operations it's not sexy it's not something you can sell saying oh your bus is coming every five minutes as opposed to every eight minutes gets a real yawn in a political type environment Atlanta's rail Advocates say that Marta's decision to allocate the money from the tax levy on improving bus operations defies the will of Voters what we're about is making sure there's transparency and accountability and what our public officials and public institutions are doing with the money that we're giving them to achieve an outcome and if there isn't enough money to build the projects that Marta said it could build for the money we said we would pay then I think it's up to agencies like Marta and our leaders at the city to tell us that and to give us the opportunity as to how to react to that there was a package of things the belt line was one of the things in the package and there were other things in that package including increased bus service and making sure that there was some better technology on The Rail lines we really don't know and I don't think they know why this passed and I should also note that there has to be some ability for a Transit Agency to make some types of minor changes when a major world-changing event like covid-19 happens you know Marta didn't know what that kova 19 was going to happen and they certainly could not have projected what changes were going to happen as a result of that the two coveted relief bills one signed by Trump the other by Biden sent 69 billion dollars in additional funding to America's Transit agencies at a time when ridership is falling this country for basically as long as you and I have been alive has been under investing in rail Pete bootage is of course running for president and so he's going to say things that a politician would if you spend more money on rail projects where they're not needed which is most places in the country you're going to be wasting your money I think if Pete bootage would go down a couple floors in the D.O.T building and talk to his Transit planners and it's folks that who have been there for more than five minutes he would realize that this doesn't necessarily make a lot of sense it means you're going to have fewer bus lines that you need because spending money on rail is inherently going to take money from bus it means you're going to have fewer transportation resources that you need probably roadways but could be other things such as bike lanes and sidewalks you're going to be spending funds that you just don't need in an economy that is already overheated Buddha judge has been a Critic of how cars reshaped the national landscape he said that the interstate highway system is systemically racist because it cut through historic black and immigrant neighborhoods if the highway was built for the purpose of dividing a white in the black neighborhood or if an underpass was constructed such that a bus carrying mostly black and Puerto Rican kids to a beach or they would have been in New York was was designed too low for it to pass by but that obviously reflects racism that went into those design choices you can question whether we should have built the highway system in the exact form that we did I think those are all fair questions but this idea that somehow we spent a lot of money on highways and so now it's time to spend a lot of money on Railways because that's just the right thing to do or that's just going to solve our problems magically it doesn't pencil out buses replaced rail not because of conspiracy but because they're much more flexible and cost effective Transit should cater to what customers want which fast and convenient point-to-point Mobility reimagining what Transit is which is it's not just an agency it's services that are provided to your customers which are people who are paying for and so we're not just talking about fixed Rail and bus we're talking about the Ubers and lifts we're talking about on-demand Transit we're talking about microtransit which is Transit that isn't travel on a fixed route it might go based on where it's needed we're talking about vanpool we're talking about sort of a concept of Mobility that might not in some cases involve people owning cars which is okay if they don't want to own a car and we have a system that works for them but I think that type of approach is going to be much better than forcing people to give up cars because we make it so difficult to drive paris's walkability is what first inspired Ryan gravel to reimagine the Atlanta cityscape in the late 90s today feigenbaum suggests looking to France for a different lesson about Mobility France which is not exactly known for being a free market capitalist Capital the private sector operates all of their transit services and it's much better you'd also need some type of vouchers to make sure that the lower income folks who are the most dependent on Transit can actually access that and can reach the jobs in other places that they need to go but I think this is the time we need to start asking those questions because in the wake of covid we're not going to get back to the ridership we had in 2019 and the ridership we had in 2019 won that good anyway is there a sense in which you know the American city is just different from a city like Paris and or can't graphed that onto a place like Atlanta do you worry that you were kind of fighting an inevitable growth pattern no no not at all uh I'm not worried about that at all you know Atlanta's not Paris Atlanta's not New York Atlanta's not Houston you know like Atlanta is Atlanta and Atlanta needs to grow in the way that it grows into the best version of itself Atlanta's histories railroads its future is also railroads Marta still hasn't committed to building rail on the Beltline and says the issue still needs two more years of study before the board can vote on it the rail Advocates we spoke to worry that by then it will be too late to qualify for federal funding for a project that's taken more than 20 years already gravel is right that Rail lines were good for American cities because they were heavily used and often profitable so what are the chances that today a project expected from the outset to operate at a loss during a period of declining rail Transit use and that depends on over a hundred million dollars in federal subsidies is going to be something that Atlanta commuters actually use foreign

Atlanta (/√¶tÀàl√¶nt…ô/) is the capital and most populous city of the U.S. state of Georgia. With an estimated 2019 population of 506,811,[10] it is also the 37th most populous city in the United States. The city serves as the cultural and economic center of the Atlanta metropolitan area, home to more than six million people and the ninth-largest metropolitan area in the nation.[8] Atlanta is the seat of Fulton County, the most populous county in Georgia. Portions of the city extend eastward into neighboring DeKalb County. The city is situated among the foothills of the Appalachian Mountains and has the highest elevation among major cities east of the Mississippi River.[13]
Atlanta was originally founded as the terminus of a major state-sponsored railroad. With rapid expansion, however, it soon became the convergence point among multiple railroads, spurring its rapid growth. The city's name derives from that of the Western and Atlantic Railroad's local depot, signifying the town's growing reputation as a transportation hub.[14] During the American Civil War, the city was almost entirely burned to the ground in General William T. Sherman's March to the Sea. However, the city rose from its ashes and quickly became a national center of commerce and the unofficial capital of the "New South". During the 1950s and 1960s, Atlanta became a major organizing center of the civil rights movement, with Martin Luther King Jr., Ralph David Abernathy, and many other locals playing major roles in the movement's leadership.[15] During the modern era, Atlanta has attained international prominence as a major air transportation hub, with Hartsfield‚ÄìJackson Atlanta International Airport being the world's busiest airport by passenger traffic since 1998.[16][17][18][19]
It ranks in the top twenty among world cities and 10th in the nation with a gross domestic product (GDP) of $385 billion.[20][21] Atlanta's economy is considered diverse, with dominant sectors that include aerospace, transportation, logistics, professional and business services, media operations, medical services, and information technology.[22] Atlanta has topographic features that include rolling hills and dense tree coverage, earning it the nickname of "the city in a forest".[23] Gentrification of Atlanta's neighborhoods, initially spurred by the 1996 Summer Olympics, has intensified in the 21st century with the growth of the Atlanta Beltline, altering the city's demographics, politics, aesthetic, and culture.[24][25][26]

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
The eviction moratorium applies to federally sponsored and funded housing units and developments. These entities include the Atlanta Housing Authority, Atlanta Beltline Inc., Fulton County/City of Atlanta Land Bank Authority, Invest Atlanta, Partners for Home and the City of Atlanta‚Äôs Department of Grants and Community Development.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî-
Bottoms has also extended an order that prevents the termination of water service due to non-payment through January 31.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
Bottoms has also extended hazard pay for front-line City of Atlanta employees, which will continue on a month-by-month basis until a vaccine is available and/or the City of Atlanta has resumed operation of services in the physical workplace.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

We Can‚Äôt Cop Cars Without Seeing Cop Cars‚Äù is a site specific installation by artist/scholar Dr. Fahamu Pecou. The installation features a short film by the same title displayed within a modified Ford Crown Victoria Interceptor.
Crown Victoria Interceptors are a popular vehicle used in police forces across the country. When decommissioned, they are repurposed and sold at auto auctions, often purchased by Black men in urban communities. The irony of the Crown Victoria being a popular car amongst Black men can‚Äôt be overstated, but the silhouette of the vehicle continues to have a visceral affect.

The project explores the notion of Black leisure by highlighting spaces where Black men can experience freedom, autonomy, and joy. Few representations of Black life depict these images or even considers these as valid experiences. We Can‚Äôt Cop‚Ä¶ uses cars as an allegorical as well as a literal suggestion of movement and escapism from the stresses and traumas of the world. From fear, to triumph, to joy and back to reality, the short film uses the aesthetics of magical realism to give viewers a momentary glimpse into the complex emotional landscape of Black male masculinity.‚Äù Written and Directed by Fahamu Pecou
